{
  "texts": [
    "Depending on where the source lies within this caustic pattern it can be magnified or de-magnified.",
    "Due to the relative velocity of observer, lens, microlenses, and quasar, which is of the order of 1 θ E per decade (Mosquera and Kochanek 2011), we expect to see significant variations (∼1 mag) of the microlensing magnification as the quasar emitting regions cross caustics and areas of demagnification.",
    "Moreover, because the quasar region(s) emitting at any given wavelength can vary in size, there is a chromatic dependence of this (de)magnification.",
    "It is important to note that quasars are intrinsically variable objects, therefore, in order to obtain the microlensing signal (in a single epoch or as a function of time) one needs to cleanly subtract this intrinsic variability after taking into account the time delays per multiple image due to the presence of the lensing galaxy (see Birrer et al. 2024).",
    "From an observer's point of view, one may wonder which kind of data are needed in order to use microlensing for one of the above mentioned science applications."
  ]
}